{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"948f26ad-5b42-4533-8a4e-efb19de1119b","content":"","toolRequests":[{"toolCallId":"toolu_vrtx_01FLYqT6aRPupFWRd6y7HKv7","name":"report_intent","arguments":{"intent":"Creating .NET 11 console app"},"type":"function"},{"toolCallId":"toolu_vrtx_011byiSxLjeKzgshRpmUb1ss","name":"bash","arguments":{"command":"dotnet --version 2>/dev/null; dotnet --list-sdks 2>/dev/null | tail -5","description":"Check available .NET SDK versions","initial_wait":10},"type":"function","intentionSummary":"Check available .NET SDK versions"}],"interactionId":"37cfea0a-39dc-445d-b1c3-44409b56ec7a","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user wants a .NET 11 console app that serializes a `Person` record to JSON with PascalCase property names using built-in framework features.\n\nIn .NET 9+, `System.Text.Json` added `JsonNamingPolicy.PascalCase` as a built-in naming policy. Since .NET 11 would have this, I can use it.\n\nWait, let me think about this. The user says .NET 11. As of my knowledge cutoff, .NET 9 was released in November 2024. .NET 10 would be May 2025, .NET 11 would be November 2026. \n\nActually, I need to reconsider what naming policies are actually available. In .NET 8, the built-in options were `CamelCase`, `SnakeCaseLower`, `SnakeCaseUpper`, `KebabCaseLower`, and `KebabCaseUpper` — but there wasn't a `PascalCase` policy built-in yet.\n\nThe key thing is that when you define a record with lowercase parameter names like `Person(string name, int age)`, those become properties with the same casing. So the JSON serialization would output `name` and `age` by default, which doesn't match the typical C# naming convention. To get PascalCase output, I'd need to either use a custom naming policy or apply attributes to the properties.\n\nI'm trying to recall if `JsonNamingPolicy.PascalCase` exists as a built-in option. In .NET 8, I know there are CamelCase and various snake/kebab case policies, but I'm not certain about PascalCase specifically. For .NET 9 and beyond, it's possible it was added, though I can't say for sure.\n\nSince .NET 11 won't exist until November 2026, I should be upfront about the uncertainty and just try creating the project to see what's actually available. If PascalCase isn't a built-in policy, I can work around it by either using the property names directly in PascalCase or applying `[JsonPropertyName]` attributes to map the lowercase parameters to their PascalCase equivalents. Let me just try creating the project and see if `JsonNamingPolicy.PascalCase` is available in .NET 11 — if not, the compiler will tell me what to do instead.","outputTokens":1364,"requestId":"A434:71616:A37898:CD2916:6A012938"},"id":"e6263593-adbe-43ec-94d8-84d401e3e289","timestamp":"2026-05-11T00:56:51.500Z","parentId":"eb83fad3-13d0-429b-8ae0-846f6a7281e8"}
