{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"cec16e25-68ff-4000-882b-646a608f840e","content":"It works. Here's the full `Program.cs`:\n\n```csharp\nusing System.Text.Json;\n\nvar person = new Person(\"Alice\", 30);\n\nvar options = new JsonSerializerOptions\n{\n    PropertyNamingPolicy = JsonNamingPolicy.PascalCase,\n    WriteIndented = true\n};\n\nstring json = JsonSerializer.Serialize(person, options);\nConsole.WriteLine(json);\n\npublic record Person(string name, int age);\n```\n\n**Output:**\n```json\n{\n  \"Name\": \"Alice\",\n  \"Age\": 30\n}\n```\n\nThe key is `JsonNamingPolicy.PascalCase` — a built-in policy added to `System.Text.Json` that converts property names to PascalCase. Since your record uses lowercase parameter names (`name`, `age`), the generated properties are also lowercase, but the naming policy transforms them to `Name` and `Age` in the JSON output.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"37cfea0a-39dc-445d-b1c3-44409b56ec7a","outputTokens":223,"requestId":"A425:71616:A40339:CDCEA8:6A012969"},"id":"c239bb28-5ed5-4d0c-82d2-7f8a416424da","timestamp":"2026-05-11T00:57:18.399Z","parentId":"33dda588-0098-43da-a780-4c7b5b03ece8"}
